# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vlan-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Portions of the network that are VLAN-aware (i.e., IEEE 802.1Q conformant) can include VLAN tags.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] When a frame enters the VLAN-aware portion of the network, a tag is added to represent the VLAN membership.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Each frame must be distinguishable as being within exactly one VLAN.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] A frame in the VLAN-aware portion of the network that does not contain a VLAN tag is assumed to be flowing on the **native VLAN**.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The standard was developed by IEEE 802.1, a working group of the IEEE 802 standards committee, and continues to be actively revised with notable amendments including IEEE 802.1ad, IEEE 802.1ak and IEEE 802.1s.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The 802.1Q-2014 revision incorporated the IEEE 802.1D-2004 standard, which originally defined bridging and Spanning Tree Protocol.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] 802.1Q adds a 32-bit field between the source MAC address and the EtherType fields of the original frame.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Under 802.1Q, the maximum frame size is extended from 1,518 bytes to 1,522 bytes.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The minimum frame size remains 64 bytes, but a bridge may extend the minimum frame size from 64 to 68 bytes on transmission.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] This allows a tag to be popped without needing additional padding.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Two bytes are used for the tag protocol identifier (TPID), the other two bytes for tag control information (TCI).
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The TCI field is further divided into PCP, DEI, and VID.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] in order to identify the frame as an IEEE 802.1Q-tagged frame.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] This field is located at the same position as the EtherType field in untagged frames, and is thus used to distinguish the frame from untagged frames.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Different PCP values can be used to prioritize different classes of traffic.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] ) May be used separately or in conjunction with PCP to indicate frames eligible to be dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] A 12-bit field specifying the VLAN to which the frame belongs.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] All other values may be used as VLAN identifiers, allowing up to 4,094 VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The VID value 0xFFF is reserved for implementation use; it must not be configured or transmitted.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] 0xFFF can be used to indicate a wildcard match in management operations or filtering database entries.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] In other words, the VLAN tag follows the SNAP header.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] For 802.3 frames in LLC-SNAP format, the order is opposite; the VLAN tag is placed *before* the LLC-SNAP header.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Because inserting the VLAN tag changes the frame, 802.1Q encapsulation forces a recalculation of the original frame check sequence field in the Ethernet trailer.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The IEEE 802.3ac standard increased the maximum Ethernet frame size from 1518 bytes to 1522 bytes to accommodate the four-byte VLAN tag.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Some network devices that do not support the larger frame size will process these frames successfully but may report them as *baby giant* anomalies.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] IEEE 802.1ad introduced the concept of double tagging.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] Double tagging can be useful for Internet service providers (ISPs), allowing them to use their VLANs internally while carrying traffic from clients that is already VLAN tagged.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The outer (next to the source MAC and representing ISP VLAN) S-TAG (service tag) comes first, followed by the inner C-TAG (customer tag).
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] In such cases, 802.1ad specifies a TPID of 0x88a8 for service-provider outer S-TAG.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] IEEE 802.1Q defines the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), an application of the Multiple Registration Protocol, allowing bridges to negotiate the set of VLANs to be used over a specific link.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] MVRP replaced the slower GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) in 2007 with the IEEE 802.1ak-2007 amendment.
[src:vlan-networking/ieee-802-1q] The 2003 revision of the standard was the first to include the Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), which was originally defined in IEEE 802.1s.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:vlan-networking/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The **Spanning Tree Protocol**(**STP**) is a network protocol that builds a loop-free logical topology for Ethernet networks.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The basic function of STP is to prevent bridge loops and the broadcast radiation that results from them.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Spanning tree also allows a network design to include backup links providing fault tolerance if an active link fails.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] As the name suggests, STP creates a spanning tree that characterizes the relationship of nodes within a network of connected layer-2 bridges, and disables those links that are not part of the spanning tree, leaving a single active path between any two network nodes.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] STP is based on an algorithm that was invented by Radia Perlman while she was working for Digital Equipment Corporation.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In 2001, the IEEE introduced **Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol** (**RSTP**) as 802.1w.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP provides significantly faster recovery in response to network changes or failures, introducing new convergence behaviors and bridge port roles to do this.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP was designed to be backwards-compatible with standard STP.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] STP was originally standardized as IEEE 802.1D but the functionality of spanning tree (802.1D), rapid spanning tree (802.1w), and Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1s) has since been incorporated into IEEE 802.1Q-2014.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] While STP is still in use today, in many modern networks its primary use is as a loop-protection mechanism rather than a fault tolerance mechanism.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Link aggregation protocols such as LACP bond multiple links to provide link-level fault tolerance while simultaneously increasing overall link capacity.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] However, implementing switch-level redundancy requires multi-chassis link aggregation, of which only proprietary variants exist.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Shortest Path Bridging combines both loop-free forwarding and link aggregation, but hasn't reached STP's or LACP's popularity yet, as of 2026.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] with Spanning Tree Protocol implementation in a local area network (LAN).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] After link failure, the spanning tree algorithm computes and spans a new least-cost tree.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The need for the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) arose because switches in local area networks (LANs) are often interconnected using redundant links to improve resilience should one connection fail.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] However, this connection configuration creates a switching loop resulting in broadcast radiations and MAC table instability.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If redundant links are used to connect switches, then switching loops need to be avoided.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] To avoid the problems associated with redundant links in a switched LAN, STP is implemented on switches to monitor the network topology.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Every link between switches, and in particular redundant links, is catalogued.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The spanning-tree algorithm then blocks forwarding on redundant links by setting up one preferred link between switches in the LAN.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] This preferred link is used for all Ethernet frames unless it fails, in which case a non-preferred redundant link is enabled.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When implemented in a network, STP designates one layer-2 switch as *root bridge*.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] All switches then select their best connection towards the root bridge for forwarding and block other redundant links.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] All switches constantly communicate with their neighbors in the LAN using § Bridge protocol data units (BPDUs).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Provided there is more than one link between two switches, the STP root bridge calculates the cost of each path based on bandwidth.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] STP will select the path with the lowest cost, that is, the highest bandwidth, as the preferred link.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] STP will enable this preferred link as the only path to be used for Ethernet frames between the two switches, and disable all other possible links by designating the switch ports that connect the preferred path as *root port*.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] After STP-enabled switches in a LAN have elected the root bridge, all non-root bridges assign one of their ports as a root port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] This is either the port that connects the switch to the root bridge, or if there are several paths, the port with the preferred path as calculated by the root bridge.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Because not all switches are directly connected to the root bridge, they communicate amongst each other using STP BPDUs.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Each switch adds the cost of its own path to the cost received from the neighboring switches to determine the total cost of a given path to the root bridge.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Once the cost of all possible paths to the root bridge has been added up, each switch assigns a port as a root port that connects to the path with the lowest cost, or highest bandwidth, that will eventually lead to the root bridge.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The STP path cost default was originally calculated by the formula ⁠1 Gbit/s/bandwidth⁠.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When faster speeds became available, the default values were adjusted as otherwise speeds above 1 Gbit/s would have been indistinguishable by STP.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Its successor RSTP uses a similar formula with a larger numerator: ⁠20 Tbit/s/bandwidth⁠.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] These formulas lead to the sample values in the table.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] All switch ports in the LAN where STP is enabled are categorized.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A port that would cause a switching loop if it were active.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] To prevent the use of looped paths, no user data is sent or received over a blocking port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] BPDU data is still received in the blocking state.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A blocked port may go into forwarding mode if the other links in use fail and the spanning tree algorithm determines that the port may transition to the forwarding state.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The switch processes BPDUs and awaits possible new information that would cause it to return to the blocking state.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] While the port does not yet forward frames, it does learn source addresses from frames received and adds them to the MAC table.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A port in normal operation receiving and forwarding frames.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The port monitors incoming BPDUs that would indicate it should return to the blocking state to prevent a loop.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A network administrator has manually disabled the switch port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When a device is first attached to a switch port, it will not immediately start to forward data.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] It will instead go through a number of states while it processes BPDUs and determines the topology of the network.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The port attached to a host such as a computer, printer or server always goes into the forwarding state, albeit after a delay of about 30 seconds while it goes through the listening and learning states.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The time spent in the listening and learning states is determined by a value known as the forward delay (default 15 seconds and set by the root bridge).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If another switch is connected, the port may remain in blocking mode if it is determined that it would cause a loop in the network.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Topology change notification (TCN) BPDUs are used to inform other switches of port changes.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] TCNs are injected into the network by a non-root switch and propagated to the root.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Upon receipt of the TCN, the root switch will set the topology change flag in its normal BPDUs.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] This flag is propagated to all other switches and instructs them to rapidly age out their forwarding table entries.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Before configuring STP, the network topology should be carefully planned.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Basic configuration requires that STP be enabled on all switches in the LAN and the same version of STP chosen on each.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The administrator may determine which switch will be the root bridge and configure the switches appropriately.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If the root bridge goes down, the protocol will automatically assign a new root bridge based on bridge ID.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If all switches have the same bridge ID, such as the default ID, and the root bridge goes down, a tie situation arises and the protocol will assign one switch as the root bridge based on the switch's MAC addresses.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Once the switches have been assigned a bridge ID and the protocol has chosen the root bridge switch, the best path to the root bridge is calculated based on port cost, path cost and port priority.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Ultimately, STP calculates the path cost on the basis of the bandwidth of a link.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Administrators can influence the protocol's choice of the preferred path by configuring the port cost; the lower the port cost, the more likely it is that the protocol will choose the connected link as root port for the preferred path.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The selection of how other switches in the topology choose their root port, or the least cost path to the root bridge, can be influenced by the port priority.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The highest priority will mean the path will ultimately be less preferred.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If all ports of a switch have the same priority, the port with the lowest number is chosen to forward frames.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The *root bridge* of the spanning tree is the bridge with the smallest (lowest) bridge ID.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Each bridge has a configurable priority number and a MAC address; the bridge ID is the concatenation of the bridge priority and the MAC address.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The bridge priority default is 32,768 and can be configured only in multiples of 4096.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When comparing two bridge IDs, the priority portions are compared first and the MAC addresses are compared only if the priorities are equal.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The switch with the lowest priority of all the switches will be the root; if there is a tie, then the switch with the lowest priority and lowest MAC address will be the root.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If the network administrators would like switch *B* to become the root bridge, they must set its priority to be less than 32,768.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When multiple paths from a bridge are least-cost paths, the chosen path uses the neighbor bridge with the lower bridge ID.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The root port is thus the one connecting to the bridge with the lowest bridge ID.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] d instead of segment f, there would be two paths of length 2 to the root, one path going through bridge 24 and the other through bridge 92.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Because there are two least-cost paths, the lower bridge ID (24) would be used as the tiebreaker in choosing which path to use.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When more than one bridge on a segment leads to a least-cost path to the root, the bridge with the lower bridge ID is used to forward messages to the root.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In the figures, there are two least-cost paths from network segment d to the root, one going through bridge 24 and the other through bridge 92.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The lower bridge ID is 24, so the tiebreaker dictates that the designated port is the port through which network segment d is connected to bridge 24.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If bridge IDs were equal, then the bridge with the lowest MAC address would have the designated port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In either case, the loser sets the port as being blocked.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] When the root bridge has more than one port on a single network segment, the bridge ID is effectively tied, as are all root path costs (all equal zero).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The port on that network segment with the lowest port ID becomes the designated port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] It is put into forwarding mode while all other ports on the root bridge on that same network segment become non-designated ports and are put into blocking mode.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Not all bridge manufacturers follow this rule, instead making all root bridge ports designated ports, and putting them all in forwarding mode.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In some cases, there may still be a tie, as when the root bridge has multiple active ports on the same network segment (see above) with equally low root path costs and bridge IDs, or, in other cases, multiple bridges are connected by multiple cables and multiple ports.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In each case, a single bridge may have multiple candidates for its root port.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In these cases, candidates for the root port have already received BPDUs offering equally-low (i.e. the "best") root path costs and equally-low (i.e. the "best") bridge IDs, and the final tiebreaker goes to the port that received the lowest (i.e. the "best") port priority ID, or port ID.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The above rules describe one way of determining what spanning tree will be computed by the algorithm, but the rules as written require knowledge of the entire network.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The bridges have to determine the root bridge and compute the port roles (root, designated, or blocked) with only the information that they have.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] To ensure that each bridge has enough information, the bridges use special data frames called bridge protocol data units (BPDUs) to exchange information about the Spanning Tree Protocol, bridge IDs, and root path costs.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] , and may be used instead of the standard.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A bridge sends a BPDU frame using the unique MAC address of the port itself as a source address.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Combined length of the LLC Header, BPDU payload, and FCS.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] BPDUs are exchanged regularly (every 2 seconds by default) and enable switches to keep track of network changes and to start and stop forwarding at ports as required.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] To prevent the delay when connecting hosts to a switch and during some topology changes, Rapid STP was developed, which allows a switch port to rapidly transition into the forwarding state during these situations.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] There are two types of BPDUs in the original STP specification (802.1D) (the Rapid Spanning Tree (RSTP) extension uses a specific RSTP BPDU).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Topology change notification (TCN) BPDU, used to announce changes in the network topology, such as port up or port down.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Proposal in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 01 for Port Role Alternate/Backup in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 10 for Port Role Root in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 11 for Port Role Designated in RST/MST/SPT BPD.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Learning in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Forwarding in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Agreement in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] 0 or 1 for Topology Change Acknowledgement.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Configuration BPDU (CBPDU), used for spanning tree computation and sent by root bridges to provide information to all switches.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The first Spanning Tree Protocol was invented in 1985 at the Digital Equipment Corporation by Radia Perlman.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In 1990, the IEEE published the first standard for the protocol as 802.1D, based on the algorithm designed by Perlman.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Subsequent versions were published in 1998 and 2004, incorporating various extensions.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The original Perlman-inspired Spanning Tree Protocol, called DEC STP, is not a standard and differs from the IEEE version in message format as well as timer settings.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Some bridges implement both the IEEE and the DEC versions of the Spanning Tree Protocol, but their interworking can create issues for the network administrator.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Different implementations of a standard are not guaranteed to interoperate, due, for example, to differences in default timer settings.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The IEEE encourages vendors to provide a Protocol Implementation Conformance Statement, declaring which capabilities and options have been implemented, to help users determine whether different implementations will interoperate correctly.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In 2001, the IEEE introduced Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP) as **IEEE 802.1w**.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP was then incorporated into IEEE 802.1D-2004, making the original STP standard obsolete.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP was designed to be backward-compatible with standard STP.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP provides significantly faster spanning tree convergence after a topology change, introducing new convergence behaviors and bridge port roles to accomplish this.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] While STP can take 30 to 50 seconds to respond to a topology change, RSTP is typically able to respond to changes within 3 × *hello times* (default: 3 × 2 seconds) or within a few milliseconds of a physical link failure.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The hello time is an important and configurable time interval that is used by RSTP for several purposes; its default value is 2 seconds.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] STP and RSTP do not segregate switch ports by VLAN.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] However, in Ethernet switched environments where multiple VLANs exist, it is often desirable to create multiple spanning trees so that traffic on different VLANs uses different links.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Before the IEEE published a Spanning Tree Protocol standard for VLANs, a number of vendors who sold VLAN-capable switches developed their own Spanning Tree Protocol versions that were VLAN capable.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco developed, implemented and published the **Per-VLAN Spanning Tree** (**PVST**) proprietary protocol using its own proprietary Inter-Switch Link (ISL) for VLAN encapsulation, and PVST+ which uses 802.1Q VLAN encapsulation.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Both standards implement a separate spanning tree for every VLAN.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco switches now commonly implement PVST+ and can only implement Spanning Trees for VLANs if the other switches in the LAN implement the same VLAN STP protocol.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] HP provides PVST and PVST+ compatibility in some of its network switches.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Some devices from Force10 Networks, Alcatel-Lucent, Extreme Networks, Avaya, Brocade Communications Systems and BLADE Network Technologies support PVST+.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Extreme Networks does so with two limitations: Lack of support on ports where the VLAN is untagged/native, and also on the VLAN with ID 1.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The switch vendor Juniper Networks in turn developed and implemented its VLAN Spanning Tree Protocol (VSTP) to provide compatibility with Cisco's PVST, so that the switches from both vendors can be included in one LAN.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The VSTP protocol is only supported by the EX and MX Series from Juniper Networks.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] If this protocol is in use, VLAN membership for trunk interfaces must be statically configured.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] By default, VSTP uses the RSTP protocol as its core spanning-tree protocol, but usage of STP can be forced if the network includes old bridges.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] More information about configuring VSTP on Juniper Networks switches was published in the official documentation.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco also published a proprietary version of Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] It creates a spanning tree for each VLAN, just like PVST.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco refers to this as **Rapid Per-VLAN Spanning Tree** (**RPVST**).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), originally defined in IEEE 802.1s-2002 and later merged into IEEE 802.1Q-2005, defines an extension to RSTP to further develop the usefulness of VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In the standard, a spanning tree that maps one or more VLANs is called a *multiple spanning tree* (MST).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Under MSTP, a spanning tree can be defined for individual VLANs or for groups of VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Furthermore, the administrator can define alternate paths within a spanning tree.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Switches are first assigned to an MST region, then VLANs are mapped against or assigned to this MST.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A *common spanning tree* (CST) is an MST to which several VLANs are mapped; this group of VLANs is called *MST instance* (MSTI).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] CSTs are backward compatible with the STP and RSTP standards.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] A MST that has only one VLAN assigned to it is an *internal spanning tree* (IST).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Unlike some proprietary per-VLAN spanning tree implementations, MSTP includes all of its spanning tree information in a single BPDU format.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Not only does this reduce the number of BPDUs required to communicate spanning tree information for each VLAN, but it also ensures backward compatibility with RSTP and, in effect, classic STP too.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP does this by encoding an additional region of information after the standard RSTP BPDU as well as a number of MSTI messages (from 0 to 64 instances, although in practice many bridges support fewer).
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Each of these MSTI configuration messages conveys the spanning tree information for each instance.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Each instance can be assigned a number of configured VLANs and frames assigned to these VLANs operate in this spanning tree instance whenever they are inside the MST region.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In order to avoid conveying their entire VLAN to spanning tree mapping in each BPDU, bridges encode an MD5 digest of their VLAN to the instance table in the MSTP BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] This digest is then used by other MSTP bridges, along with other administratively configured values, to determine if the neighboring bridge is in the same MST region as itself.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP is fully compatible with RSTP bridges in that an MSTP BPDU can be interpreted by an RSTP bridge as an RSTP BPDU.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] This not only allows compatibility with RSTP bridges without configuration changes but also causes any RSTP bridges outside of an MSTP region to see the region as a single RSTP bridge, regardless of the number of MSTP bridges inside the region itself.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In order to further facilitate this view of an MSTP region as a single RSTP bridge, the MSTP protocol uses a variable known as remaining hops as a time-to-live counter instead of the message age timer used by RSTP.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The message age time is only incremented once when spanning-tree information enters an MST region, and therefore, RSTP bridges will see a region as only one *hop* in the spanning tree.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Ports at the edge of an MSTP region connected to either an RSTP or STP bridge or an endpoint are known as boundary ports.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] As in RSTP, these ports can be configured as edge ports to facilitate rapid changes to the forwarding state when connected to endpoints.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] SPB consolidates multiple existing functionalities, including Spanning Tree Protocol (STP), Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP), Link aggregation, and Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP) into a one link state protocol.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The bridge ID (BID) is a field inside a BPDU packet.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The first two bytes are the bridge priority, an unsigned integer of 0–65,535.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] The last six bytes are a MAC address supplied by the bridge.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Prior to IEEE 802.1D-2004, the first two bytes gave a 16-bit bridge priority.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Since IEEE 802.1D-2004, the first four bits are a configurable priority, and the last twelve bits carry the bridge system ID extension.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] In the case of MST, the bridge system ID extension carries the MSTP instance number.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Some vendors set the bridge system ID extension to carry a VLAN ID, allowing a different spanning tree per VLAN, such as Cisco's PVST.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Spanning tree is an older protocol with a longer convergence time.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Improper use or implementation can contribute to network disruptions.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Blocking links is a crude approach to high availability and preventing loops.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Modern networks can make use of all connected links by use of protocols that inhibit, control or suppress the natural behavior of logical or physical topology loops.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Newer, more robust protocols include the TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) protocol, also created by Perlman, and Shortest Path Bridging from the IEEE.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Configuring connections between network equipment as layer-3 IP links and relying on IP routing for resiliency and to prevent loops is a popular alternative.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Switch virtualization techniques like Cisco Virtual Switching System and Virtual PortChannel and HP Intelligent Resilient Framework combine multiple switches into a single logical entity.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Such a multi-chassis link aggregation group works like a normal port trunk, only distributed through multiple switches.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] Conversely, partitioning technologies compartmentalize a single physical chassis into multiple logical entities.
[src:vlan-networking/spanning-tree-protocol] On the edge of the network, loop detection is configured to prevent accidental loops by users.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] A **virtual local area network** (**VLAN**) is a local area network broadcast domain that is partitioned and isolated in a virtual network at the data link layer (OSI layer 2).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] A VLAN behaves like a virtual network switch or network link that can share the same physical structure with other VLANs while staying logically separate from them.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs work by applying tags to network frames that are forwarded within the broadcast domain, creating the appearance and functionality of network traffic that behaves as if it were split between separate networks.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In this way, VLANs can keep network applications separate despite being connected to the same physical network, and without requiring multiple sets of cabling and networking devices to be deployed.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs allow network administrators to group hosts together even if the hosts are not directly connected to the same network switch.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Because VLAN membership can be configured through software, this can greatly simplify network design and deployment.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Without VLANs, grouping hosts according to their resources requires relocating nodes or rewiring data links.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs allow devices that must be kept separate to share the cabling of a physical network and yet be prevented from directly interacting with one another.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This managed sharing yields gains in simplicity, security, traffic control, and economy.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Many Internet hosting services use VLANs to separate customers' private zones from one another, enabling each customer's servers to be grouped within a single network segment regardless of where the individual servers are located in the data center.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Some precautions are needed to prevent traffic "escaping" from a given VLAN, an exploit known as VLAN hopping.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] To subdivide a network into VLANs, one configures network equipment.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Simpler equipment might partition only each physical port, in which case each VLAN runs over a dedicated network cable.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] More sophisticated devices can mark frames through VLAN tagging, so that a single interconnect (*trunk*) may be used to transport data for multiple VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Since VLANs share bandwidth, a VLAN trunk can use link aggregation, quality-of-service prioritization, or both to route data efficiently.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs address issues such as scalability, security, and network management.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Network architects set up VLANs to provide network segmentation.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Routers between VLANs filter broadcast traffic, enhance network security, perform address summarization, and mitigate network congestion.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In a network utilizing broadcasts for service discovery, address assignment and resolution and other services, as the number of peers on a network grows, the frequency of broadcasts also increases.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs can help manage broadcast traffic by forming multiple broadcast domains.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Breaking up a large network into smaller independent segments reduces the amount of broadcast traffic each network device and network segment has to bear.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Switches may not bridge network traffic between VLANs, as doing so would violate the integrity of the VLAN broadcast domain.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs can also help create multiple layer 3 networks on a single physical infrastructure.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs are data link layer (OSI layer 2) constructs, analogous to Internet Protocol (IP) subnets, which are network layer (OSI layer 3) constructs.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In an environment employing VLANs, a one-to-one relationship often exists between VLANs and IP subnets, although it is possible to have multiple subnets on one VLAN.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Without VLAN capability, users are assigned to networks based on geography and are limited by physical topologies and distances.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs can logically group networks to decouple the users' network location from their physical location.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] By using VLANs, one can control traffic patterns and react quickly to employee or equipment relocations.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs provide the flexibility to adapt to changes in network requirements and allow for simplified administration.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] A common infrastructure shared across VLAN trunks can provide a measure of security with great flexibility for a comparatively low cost.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Quality of service schemes can optimize traffic on trunk links for real-time (e.g.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] However, VLANs as a security solution should be implemented with great care as they can be defeated unless implemented carefully.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In cloud computing VLANs, IP addresses, and MAC addresses in the cloud are resources that end users can manage.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] To help mitigate security issues, placing cloud-based virtual machines on VLANs may be preferable to placing them directly on the Internet.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] After successful experiments with voice over Ethernet from 1981 to 1984, W.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] David Sincoskie joined Bellcore and began addressing the problem of scaling up Ethernet networks.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] At 10 Mbit/s, Ethernet was faster than most alternatives at the time.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] However, Ethernet was a broadcast network and there was no good way of connecting multiple Ethernet networks together.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This limited the total bandwidth of an Ethernet network to 10 Mbit/s and the maximum distance between nodes to a few hundred feet.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] By contrast, although the existing telephone network's speed for individual connections was limited to 56 kbit/s (less than one hundredth of Ethernet's speed), the total bandwidth of that network was estimated at 1 Tbit/s (100,000 times greater than Ethernet).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Although it was possible to use IP routing to connect multiple Ethernet networks together, it was expensive and relatively slow.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Sincoskie started looking for alternatives that required less processing per packet.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In the process, he independently reinvented transparent bridging, the technique used in modern Ethernet switches.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] However, using switches to connect multiple Ethernet networks in a fault-tolerant fashion requires redundant paths through that network, which in turn requires a spanning tree configuration.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This ensures that there is only one *active* path from any source node to any destination on the network.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This causes centrally located switches to become bottlenecks, limiting scalability as more networks are interconnected.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] To help alleviate this problem, Sincoskie invented VLANs by adding a tag (an individual label, such as A, B, C, and so on) to each Ethernet frame.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In this scheme, each switch could be assigned to handle frames of a specific tag and ignore the rest.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] The networks could be interconnected with three spanning trees, one for each color.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] By sending a mix of different frame tags, the aggregate bandwidth could be improved.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Sincoskie referred to this as a *multitree bridge*.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] He and Chase Cotton created and refined the algorithms necessary to make the system feasible.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This *color* is what is now known in the Ethernet frame as the IEEE 802.1Q header, or the VLAN tag.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] While VLANs are commonly used in modern Ethernet networks, they are not used in the manner first envisioned here.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In 1998, Ethernet VLANs were described in the first edition of the IEEE 802.1Q-1998 standard.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This was extended with IEEE 802.1ad to allow nested VLAN tags in service of provider bridging.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This mechanism was improved with IEEE 802.1ah-2008.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Early network designers often segmented physical LANs with the aim of reducing the size of the Ethernet collision domain—thus improving performance.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] When Ethernet switches made this a non-issue (because each switch port is a collision domain), attention turned to reducing the size of the data link layer broadcast domain.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs were first employed to separate several broadcast domains across one physical medium.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] A VLAN can also serve to restrict access to network resources without regard to physical topology of the network.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLANs operate at the data link layer of the OSI model.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Administrators often configure a VLAN to map directly to an IP network, or subnet, which gives the appearance of involving the network layer.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Generally, VLANs within the same organization will be assigned different non-overlapping network address ranges.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] There is no issue with separate VLANs using identical overlapping address ranges (e.g. two VLANs each use the private network *192.168.0.0/16*).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] However, it is not possible to route data between two networks with overlapping addresses without delicate IP remapping, so if the goal of VLANs is segmentation of a larger overall organizational network, non-overlapping addresses must be used in each separate VLAN.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] A basic switch that is not configured for VLANs has VLAN functionality disabled or permanently enabled with a *default VLAN* that contains all ports on the device as members.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] The default VLAN typically uses VLAN identifier 1.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Every device connected to one of its ports can send packets to any of the others.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Separating ports by VLAN groups separates their traffic very much like connecting each group using a distinct switch for each group.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Remote management of the switch requires that the administrative functions be associated with one or more of the configured VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In the context of VLANs, the term *trunk* denotes a network link carrying multiple VLANs, which are identified by labels (or *tags*) inserted into their packets.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Such trunks must run between *tagged ports* of VLAN-aware devices, so they are often switch-to-switch or switch-to-router links rather than links to hosts.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] (Note that the term 'trunk' is also used for what Cisco calls "channels" : Link Aggregation or Port Trunking).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] A router (Layer 3 device) serves as the backbone for network traffic going across different VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] It is only when the VLAN port group is to extend to another device that tagging is used.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Since communications between ports on two different switches travel via the uplink ports of each switch involved, every VLAN containing such ports must also contain the uplink port of each switch involved, and traffic through these ports must be tagged.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Switches typically have no built-in method to indicate VLAN to port associations to someone working in a wiring closet.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] It is necessary for a technician to either have administrative access to the device to view its configuration, or for VLAN port assignment charts or diagrams to be kept next to the switches in each wiring closet.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] The protocol most commonly used today to support VLANs is IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] The IEEE 802.1 working group defined this method of multiplexing VLANs in an effort to provide multivendor VLAN support.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Prior to the introduction of the 802.1Q standard, several proprietary protocols existed, such as Cisco Inter-Switch Link (ISL) and 3Com's Virtual LAN Trunk (VLT).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Cisco also implemented VLANs over FDDI by carrying VLAN information in an IEEE 802.10 frame header, contrary to the purpose of the IEEE 802.10 standard.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Both ISL and IEEE 802.1Q perform *explicit tagging* – the frame itself is tagged with VLAN identifiers.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] ISL uses an external tagging process that does not modify the Ethernet frame, while 802.1Q uses a frame-internal field for tagging, and therefore does modify the basic Ethernet frame structure.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This internal tagging allows IEEE 802.1Q to work on both access and trunk links using standard Ethernet hardware.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Under IEEE 802.1Q, the maximum number of VLANs on a given Ethernet network is 4,094 (4,096 values provided by the 12-bit VID field minus reserved values at each end of the range, 0 and 4,095).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This does not impose the same limit on the number of IP subnets in such a network since a single VLAN can contain multiple IP subnets.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1ad extends the number of VLANs supported by adding support for multiple, nested VLAN tags.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1aq (Shortest Path Bridging) expands the VLAN limit to 16 million.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Both improvements have been incorporated into the IEEE 802.1Q standard.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Inter-Switch Link (ISL) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to interconnect switches and maintain VLAN information as traffic travels between switches on trunk links.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] ISL is provided as an alternative to IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] ISL is available only on some Cisco equipment and has been deprecated.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol that propagates the definition of VLANs on the whole local area network.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VTP is available on most of the Cisco Catalyst Family products.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) or the more recent Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol is an application of Multiple Registration Protocol that allows automatic configuration of VLAN information on network switches.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Specifically, it provides a method to dynamically share VLAN information and configure the needed VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLAN membership can be established either statically or dynamically.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Static VLANs are also referred to as port-based VLANs.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Static VLAN assignments are created by assigning ports to a VLAN.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the device automatically assumes the VLAN of the port.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] If the user changes ports and needs access to the same VLAN, the network administrator must manually make a port-to-VLAN assignment for the new connection.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Dynamic VLANs are created using software or by protocol.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] With a VLAN Management Policy Server (VMPS), an administrator can assign switch ports to VLANs dynamically based on information such as the source MAC address of the device connected to the port or the username used to log onto that device.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the switch queries a database for the VLAN membership of the port that device is connected to.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Protocol methods include Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP) and the somewhat obsolete GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP).
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] In a switch that supports protocol-based VLANs, traffic may be handled on the basis of its protocol.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] Essentially, this segregates or forwards traffic from a port depending on the particular protocol of that traffic; traffic of any other protocol is not forwarded on the port.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] This allows, for example, IP and IPX traffic to be automatically segregated by the network.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] VLAN cross connect (CC or VLAN-XC) is a mechanism used to create Switched VLANs, VLAN CC uses IEEE 802.1ad frames where the S Tag is used as a Label as in MPLS.
[src:vlan-networking/virtual-lan] IEEE approves the use of such a mechanism in part 6.11 of IEEE 802.1ad-2005.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] There are three versions of VTP, namely version 1, version 2, version 3.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GVRP or the more recent MVRP.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] On **Cisco Devices**, VTP (VLAN Trunking Protocol) maintains VLAN configuration consistency across a single Layer 2 network.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] VTP uses Layer 2 frames to manage the addition, deletion, and renaming of VLANs from switches in the VTP client mode.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] VTP is responsible for synchronizing VLAN information within a VTP domain and reduces the need to configure the same VLAN information on each switch thereby minimizing the possibility of configuration inconsistencies that arise when changes are made.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] When a new switch is added to the network, by default it is configured with no VTP domain name or password, but in VTP server mode.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] If no VTP Domain Name has been configured, it assumes the one from the first VTP packet it receives.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] Since a new switch has a VTP configuration revision of 0, it will accept any revision number as newer and overwrite its VLAN information if the VTP passwords match.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] Since Cisco switches maintain VTP configuration information separately from the normal configuration, and since this particular issue occurs so frequently, it has become known colloquially as the "VTP Bomb".
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] Before creating VLANs on the switch that will propagate via VTP, a VTP domain must first be set up.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] A VTP domain for a network is a set of all contiguously trunked switches with the matching VTP settings (domain name, password and VTP version).
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] All switches in the same VTP domain share their VLAN information with each other, and a switch can participate in only one VTP management domain.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] Switches in different domains do not share VTP information.
[src:vlan-networking/vlan-trunking-protocol] Non-matching VTP settings might result in issues in negotiating VLAN trunks, port-channels or Virtual Port Channels.
